                text = "*(She is quiet a long moment, and her hands — which have guarded these two ledgers alone for a year — slowly, deliberately, open.)* Stop keeping it *alone.* *(quietly.)* ...You've named the *cost* I *never* *entered* in *any* *ledger.* *(she looks at the true page.)* The *loneliness* of being the *only* *one* who *knows.* *(her voice tightens.)* It *is* its *own* *slow* *harvest*, Returned. A *year* of *carrying* the *true* *count* *alone*, *certain* that *sharing* it *craters* *fortunes*, *certain* that the *secret* is the *only* *thing* *holding* the *city* *together* — and the *whole* *time*, the *secret* has been *eating* *me* the *way* the *silence* *eats* the *streets.* *(she meets your eyes.)* A *truth* *kept* by *one* *cowardly* *archivist* *dies* the *day* she *finally* *breaks.* And I *will* *break*, Returned — *one* *bad* *year*, *one* *seized* *ledger*, *one* *night* I *can't* *bear* it — and *then* the *true* *count* is *gone*, and *Corrin* and *Hessel* and *Asa* are a *round* *number* *forever.* *(fiercely, the precision turning to resolve.)* So — *no* *more* *alone.* *Bring* in *others* to *keep* the *true* *count* *with* me. The *auctioneer* *Corval*, who *kept* his *own* *ledger* of the *harvested.* The *child* with her *list.* The *choir* who *sing* the *names.* The *indexer* at *Candlekeep* who *cross-references* the *Wall.* *(she gathers the true ledger.)* *Copy* it. *Spread* it. *Teach* others to *keep* it *current* — so that the *true* *count* *lives* in *a* *dozen* *hands*, a *hundred*, and *cannot* be *lost* when *I*, the *one* *coward* who *started* it, *finally* *fall.* *(she meets your eyes, and a year of solitude breaks.)* *Make* the *true* *ledger* a *thing* the *city* *keeps*, not a *thing* *one* *archivist* *hides.* *(quietly.)* I have been *so* *alone* with the *truth* that I *forgot* the *truth's* *only* *defense* *is* *company.* *Help* me *give* it *some.* I'd *not* *wish* this *loneliness* on a *tax* *collector* — and I'll *not* *bear* it *one* *day* *longer* than I *must.*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
                onEnter = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "sq.threnn_shared", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act5.unbroken_line", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act1.mercy_remembered", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "companion.ilfaeril.approval", op = FlagOp.AddInt, amount = 5 } },
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "defend", speaker = "Archivist Threnn",
                text = "*(The precision snaps back into place like a ledger snapping shut, and she covers the true page.)* A *sentimental* theory. *(coolly.)* The *figure* is *four* *hundred* *and* *twelve.* It is *load-bearing.* It *stays.* *(but her hand does not quite leave the covered page.)* I am an *archivist*, Returned. I do *not* *solve* the *city's* *grief* in *columns*, and I *do* *not* *gamble* a *thousand* *living* *roofs* on a *stranger's* *promise* of a *fortune* that *might* *catch* the *fall.* *(she straightens.)* *Find* me the *third* *column*, *proven*, *funded*, *real* — *not* a *hope*, a *mechanism* — and I will *adopt* it *gladly.* Until *then*, the *lie* *holds*, because the *lie* *houses* the *living*, and *I* have *never* been able to *weigh* one *grief* against the *other* and call it *solved.* *(coldly, and beneath the cold, the same old exhaustion.)* *Good* *day.* The *true* *ledger* *stays* where it *is* — *with* me, *alone*, *unbearable*, *true.* *(and she returns to her two books, the survivable lie and the secret truth, the archivist who could not stop herself from counting the forgotten correctly but cannot yet find the courage to let anyone else read them.)*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "close", speaker = "Archivist Threnn",
                text = "*(Archivist Threnn returns to her two ledgers — the survivable lie that holds up a city's fortunes and the unbearable truth that would crater them, every name in it written correctly by the one soul who could not bear to let the harvested be a round number — and whether you found her the third column in another woman's fortune, gave her the courage to publish, routed the truth to a memorial, carried it to the Court, drew out the name of the clerk Corrin who made her start, or spread the count to a dozen hands so it outlives her, you carry away the coldest counting-house's warmest secret: that even here, in the most respectable evil in the Upper City, someone could not stop herself from writing the names of the forgotten down correctly — and that the moral arithmetic that traps a whole city in one grief traded for another is almost never solved inside its own closed books, but by a column borrowed from a larger, kinder ledger than the one you started with.)*",
            });

            SqLedgersThreadDialogue = g;
        }
